[[File:Uvular rhotics in Europe.png|thumb|upright=1.4|Distribution of [[Guttural R#French|guttural r]] (such as {{IPA|[ʁ ʀ χ]}}) in [[Europe]] in the mid-20th century.<ref>Map based on {{Harvcoltxt|Trudgill|1974|p=220}}</ref>
{{legend|#8A7248|not usual}}
{{legend|#A88A8E|only in some educated speech}}
{{legend|#B893CB|usual in educated speech}}
{{legend|#73488A|general}}]]
Phonetic notes:
* {{IPA|/n, t, d/}} are [[Laminal consonant|laminal]] [[Denti-alveolar consonant|denti-alveolar]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|n̪}}, {{IPA link|t̪}}, {{IPA link|d̪}}]}},{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=79}}{{sfnp|Ladefoged|Maddieson|1996|p=192}} while {{IPA|/s, z/}} are dentalized laminal alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|s̪}}, {{IPA link|z̪}}]}} (commonly called 'dental'), pronounced with the blade of the tongue very close to the back of the upper front teeth, with the tip resting behind lower front teeth.{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=79}}{{sfnp|Adams|1975|p=288}}
* Word-final consonants are always released. Generally, {{IPA|/b, d, ɡ/}} are voiced throughout and {{IPA|/p, t, k/}} are unaspirated.{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=75}}
* {{IPA|/l/}} is usually apical alveolar {{IPAblink|l|l̺}} but sometimes laminal denti-alveolar {{IPAblink|l̪}}.{{sfnp|Ladefoged|Maddieson|1996|p=192}} Before {{IPA|/f, ʒ/}}, it can be realised as [[Retroflex consonant|retroflex]] {{IPAblink|ɭ}}.{{sfnp|Ladefoged|Maddieson|1996|p=192}}
* In current pronunciation, {{IPA|/ɲ/}} is merging with {{IPA|/nj/}}.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=doYT4VXnhnAC&pg=PA326&lpg=PA326&dq=/%C9%B2/+is+merging+with+/nj/+in+france&source=bl&ots=lnaybD5zcI&sig=KgM38kqEAf2D0dp_eZtS0Q9zkUI&hl=en&sa=X&ei=YOmXUemkJ6230gG8lYGwAg&ved=0CFEQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%2F%C9%B2%2F%20is%20merging%20with%20%2Fnj%2F%20in%20france&f=false Phonological Variation in French: Illustrations from Three Continents], edited by Randall Scott Gess, Chantal Lyche, Trudel Meisenburg.</ref>
* The [[velar nasal]] {{IPA|/ŋ/}} is not a native [[phoneme]] of French, but it occurs in [[loan word]]s  such as {{wikt-lang|fr|camping}}, {{wikt-lang|fr|bingo}} or {{wikt-lang|fr|kung-fu}}.{{sfnp|Wells|1989|p=44}} Some speakers who have difficulty with this consonant realise it as a sequence {{IPA|[ŋɡ]}} or replace it with {{IPA|/ɲ/}}.{{sfnp|Grevisse|Goosse|2011|loc=§32, b}}
* The approximants {{IPA|/j, ɥ, w/}} correspond to the close vowels {{IPA|/i, y, u/}}. While there are a few [[minimal pair]]s (such as {{wikt-lang|fr|loua}} {{IPA|/lu.a/}} 's/he rented' and {{wikt-lang|fr|loi}} {{IPA|/lwa/}} 'law'), there are many cases where there is free variation.{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=75}}
* Some dialects of French have a palatal lateral {{IPA|/ʎ/}} (French: ''l [[mouillé]]'', 'moistened l'), but in the modern standard variety, it has merged with {{IPA|/j/}}.{{sfnp|Grevisse|Goosse|2011|loc=§33, b}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=47}} See also [[#Glides and diphthongs|Glides and diphthongs]], below.
* The French [[Rhotic consonant|rhotic]] has a wide range of realizations: the [[voiceless uvular fricative|voiceless]] or [[voiced uvular fricative|voiced]] uvular fricatives {{IPA|[χ]}} and {{IPA|[ʁ]}} (the latter also realized as an [[approximant consonant|approximant]]), the [[uvular trill]] {{IPA|[ʀ]}}, the [[alveolar trill]] {{IPA|[r]}}, and the [[alveolar tap]] {{IPA|[ɾ]}}. These are all recognized as the [[phoneme]] {{IPA|/r/}},{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=75}} but all except {{IPA|[ʁ]}} and {{IPA|[χ]}} are considered dialectal. {{IPA|[ʁ]}} is the standard consonant. Although the voiceless {{IPA|[χ]}} is pronounced before or after a voiceless obstruent or at the end of a sentence, the voiced symbol {{IPA|[ʁ]}} is often used in phonemic transcriptions. See [[Guttural R#French|French guttural r]] and map at right.
* Velars {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/ɡ/}} may become [[Palatalization (phonetics)|palatalised]] to {{IPA|[kʲ⁓c]}} and {{IPA|[ɡʲ⁓ɟ]}} before {{IPA|/i, e, ɛ/}}, and more variably before {{IPA|/a/}}.{{sfnp|Berns|2013}} Word-final {{IPA|/k/}} may also be palatalised to {{IPA|[kʲ]}}.{{sfnp|Detey|Durand|Laks|Lyche|2016|pp=131, 415}} Velar palatalisation has traditionally been associated with working class,{{sfnp|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=42}} though recent studies suggest it is spreading to more demographics of large French cities.{{sfnp|Detey|Durand|Laks|Lyche|2016|pp=131, 415}}

