===Geminates===
Although double consonant letters appear in the orthographic form of many French words, [[gemination|geminate]] consonants are relatively rare in the pronunciation of such words. The following cases can be identified.{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|pp=149–150}}

The geminate pronunciation {{IPA|[ʁʁ]}} is found in the future and conditional forms of the verbs {{wikt-lang|fr|courir}} ('to run') and {{wikt-lang|fr|mourir}} ('to die'). The conditional form ''il mourrait'' {{IPA|[il.muʁ.ʁɛ]}} ('he would die'), for example, contrasts with the imperfect form ''il mourait'' {{IPA|[il.mu.ʁɛ]}} ('he was dying'). This is no longer true for most modern speakers, for whom {{IPA|[ʁʁ]}} has reduced to {{IPA|[ʁ]}} in all words. Other verbs that have a double {{angbr|rr}} orthographically in the future and conditional are pronounced with a simple {{IPA|[ʁ]}}: ''il pourra'' ('he will be able to'), ''il verra'' ('he will see').

When the prefix {{wikt-lang|fr|in-}} combines with a base that begins with ''n'', the resulting word is sometimes pronounced with a geminate {{IPA|[nn]}} and similarly for the variants of the same prefix ''im-'', ''il-'', ''ir-'': 
* {{wikt-lang|fr|inné}} {{IPA|[i(n).ne]}} ('innate')
* {{wikt-lang|fr|immortel}} {{IPA|[i(m).mɔʁtɛl]}} ('immortal')
* {{wikt-lang|fr|illisible}} {{IPA|[i(l).li.zibl]}} ('illegible')
* {{wikt-lang|fr|irresponsable}} {{IPA|[i(ʁ).ʁɛs.pɔ̃.sabl]}} ('irresponsible')

Other cases of optional gemination can be found in words like {{wikt-lang|fr|syllabe}} ('syllable'), {{wikt-lang|fr|grammaire}} ('grammar'), and {{wikt-lang|fr|illusion}} ('illusion'). The pronunciation of such words, in many cases, a [[spelling pronunciation]] varies by speaker and gives rise to widely varying stylistic effects.{{sfnp|Yaguello|1991|}}, cited in {{Harvcoltxt|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=51}} In particular, the gemination of consonants other than the liquids and nasals {{IPA|/m n l ʁ/}} is "generally considered affected or pedantic".{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|p=150}} Examples of stylistically marked pronunciations include {{wikt-lang|fr|addition}} {{IPA|[ad.di.sjɔ̃]}} ('addition') and {{wikt-lang|fr|intelligence}} {{IPA|[ɛ̃.tel.li.ʒɑ̃s]}} ('intelligence').

Gemination of doubled {{angbr|m}} and {{angbr|n}} is typical of the [[Languedoc]] region, as opposed to other southern accents.

A few cases of gemination do not correspond to double consonant letters in the orthography.{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|pp=151–153}} The deletion of word-internal schwas (see below), for example, can give rise to sequences of identical consonants: ''là-dedans'' {{IPA|[lad.dɑ̃]}} ('inside'), ''l'honnêteté''  {{IPA|[lɔ.nɛt.te]}} ('honesty'). Gemination is obligatory in such contexts. The elided form of the object pronoun ''l<nowiki>'</nowiki>'' ('him/her/it') can optionally (in nonstandard, popular speech) be realized as a geminate {{IPA|[ll]}} when it appears after a vowel:
*''Je l'ai vu'' {{IPA|[ʒə(l).levy]}} ('I saw it')
*''Il faut l'attraper'' {{IPA|[il.fo(l).la.tʁa.pe]}} ('it must be caught')
Finally, a word pronounced with [[#Emphatic stress|emphatic stress]] can exhibit gemination of its first syllable-initial consonant:
*'''''for'''midable'' {{IPA|[fːɔʁ.mi.dabl]}} ('terrific')
*''é'''pou'''vantable'' {{IPA|[e.pːu.vɑ̃.tabl]}} ('horrible')

===Liaison===
{{Main|Liaison (French)}}

Many words in French can be analyzed as having a "latent" final consonant that is pronounced only in certain syntactic contexts when the next word begins with a vowel. For example, the word {{wikt-lang|fr|deux}} {{IPA|/dø/}} ('two') is pronounced {{IPA|[dø]}} in isolation or before a consonant-initial word (''deux jours'' {{IPA|/dø ʒuʁ/}} → {{IPA|[dø.ʒuʁ]}} 'two days'), but in ''deux ans'' {{IPA|/døz‿ɑ̃/}} (→ {{IPA|[dø.zɑ̃]}} 'two years'), the linking or liaison consonant {{IPA|/z/}} is pronounced.

==Vowels==
[[Image:French vowel chart.svg|thumb|right|[[Vowel]]s of Parisian French, from {{Harvcoltxt|Collins|Mees|2013|pp=225–226}}. Many speakers merge {{IPA|/œ̃/}} with {{IPA|/ɛ̃/}} and {{IPA|/a/}} with {{IPA|/ɑ/}}. In the latter case, the outcome is an open central {{IPAblink|ä}} between the two (not shown on the chart).]]
Standard French contrasts up to 13 oral vowels and up to 4 nasal vowels. The schwa (in the center of the diagram next to this paragraph) is not necessarily a distinctive sound. Even though it often merges with one of the mid front rounded vowels, its patterning suggests that it is a separate phoneme (see the sub-section [[#Schwa|Schwa]] below).

