===Close vowels===
In contrast with the mid vowels, there is no tense–lax contrast in close vowels. However, non-phonemic lax (near-close) {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʏ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ}}]}} appear in the Quebec and Cajun varieties as allophones of {{IPA|/i, y, u/}} when the vowel is both phonetically short (so not before {{IPA|/v, z, ʒ, ʁ/}}) and in a closed syllable, so that e.g. ''petite'' {{IPA|[pə.t͡sɪt]}} 'small ({{abbr|f.|feminine}})' differs from ''petit'' 'small ({{abbr|m.|masculine}})' {{IPA|[pə.t͡si]}} not only in the presence of the final {{IPA|/t/}} but also in the tenseness of the {{IPA|/i/}}. Laxing is obligatory only in stressed closed syllables, but also found in other environments to various degrees.{{sfnp|Walker|1984|pp=51–60}}{{sfnp|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|pp=25–6}}

In Parisian French, {{IPA|/i, u/}} are consistently close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|u}}]}},{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=73}}{{sfnp|Lodge|2009|p=84}}{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2013|p=225}} but the exact height of {{IPA|/y/}} is somewhat debatable as it has been variously described as close {{IPAblink|y}}{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=73}}{{sfnp|Lodge|2009|p=84}} and near-close {{IPAblink|ʏ}}.{{sfnp|Collins|Mees|2013|p=225}}

===Mid vowels===
Although the mid vowels contrast in certain environments, there is limited distributional overlap so they often appear in complementary distribution. Generally, [[close-mid vowel]]s ({{IPA|/e, ø, o/}}) are found in open syllables, and [[open-mid vowel]]s ({{IPA|/ɛ, œ, ɔ/}}) are found in closed syllables. However, there are minimal pairs:{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=73}}
* open-mid {{IPA|/ɛ/}} and close-mid {{IPA|/e/}} contrast in final-position open syllables:
*: {{wikt-lang|fr|allait}} {{IPA|[a.lɛ]}} ('was going'), vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|allé}}  {{IPA|[a.le]}} ('gone');
* likewise, open-mid {{IPA|/ɔ/}} and {{IPA|/œ/}} contrast with close-mid {{IPA|/o/}} and {{IPA|/ø/}} mostly in closed monosyllables, such as these:
*: {{wikt-lang|fr|jeune}} {{IPA|[ʒœn]}} ('young'), vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|jeûne}} {{IPA|[ʒøn]}} ('fast', verb),
*: {{wikt-lang|fr|roc}} {{IPA|[ʁɔk]}} ('rock'), vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|rauque}} {{IPA|[ʁok]}} ('hoarse'),
*: {{wikt-lang|fr|Rhodes}} {{IPA|[ʁɔd]}} ('Rhodes'), vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|rôde}} {{IPA|[ʁod]}} ('[I] lurk'),
*: {{wikt-lang|fr|Paul}} {{IPA|[pɔl]}} ('Paul', masculine), vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|Paule}} {{IPA|[pol]}} ('Paule', feminine),
*: {{wikt-lang|fr|bonne}} {{IPA|[bɔn]}} ('good', feminine), vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|Beaune}} {{IPA|[bon]}} ('[[Beaune]]', the city).

Beyond the general rule, known as the ''loi de position'' among French phonologists,{{sfnp|Morin|1986}} there are some exceptions. For instance, {{IPA|/o/}} and {{IPA|/ø/}} are found in closed syllables ending in {{IPA|[z]}}, and only {{IPA|[ɔ]}} is found in closed monosyllables before {{IPA|[ʁ]}}, {{IPA|[ɲ]}}, and {{IPA|[ɡ]}}.{{sfnp|Léon|1992|p=?}}

The phonemic opposition of {{IPA|/ɛ/}} and {{IPA|/e/}} has been lost in the southern half of France, where these two sounds are found only in complementary distribution. The phonemic oppositions of {{IPA|/ɔ/}} and {{IPA|/o/}} and of {{IPA|/œ/}} and {{IPA|/ø/}} in terminal open syllables have been lost in all of France, but not in [[Belgium]], where {{wikt-lang|fr|pot}} and {{wikt-lang|fr|peau}} are still opposed as {{IPA|/pɔ/}} and {{IPA|/po/}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://research.jyu.fi/phonfr/58.html |title=Phonétique et prononciation du français pour apprenants finnophones |last1=Kalmbach |first1=Jean-Michel |last2= |first2= |date=2011 |website= |publisher= |access-date=2 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref>

===Open vowels===
The phonemic contrast between front {{IPA|/a/}} and back {{IPA|/ɑ/}} is sometimes not maintained in Standard French, which leads some researchers to reject the idea of two distinct phonemes.<ref>"Some phoneticians claim that there are two distinct ''a''s in French, but evidence from speaker to speaker and sometimes within the speech of a single speaker is too contradictory to give empirical support to this claim".{{Harvcoltxt|Casagrande|1984|p=20}}</ref> However, the distinction is still clearly maintained in other dialects such as [[Quebec French]].<ref>[http://www.ciral.ulaval.ca/phonetique/phono/r30.htm Postériorisation du / a /] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706214342/http://www.ciral.ulaval.ca/phonetique/phono/r30.htm |date=2011-07-06 }}</ref>

While there is much variation among speakers in France, a number of general tendencies can be observed. First of all, the distinction is most often preserved in word-final stressed syllables such as in these minimal pairs:
: {{wikt-lang|fr|tache}} {{IPA|/taʃ/}} → {{IPA|[taʃ]}} ('stain'), vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|tâche}} {{IPA|/tɑʃ/}} → {{IPA|[tɑʃ]}} ('task')
: {{wikt-lang|fr|patte}} {{IPA|/pat/}} → {{IPA|[pat]}} ('leg'), vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|pâte}} {{IPA|/pɑt/}} → {{IPA|[pɑt]}} ('paste, pastry')
: {{wikt-lang|fr|rat}} {{IPA|/ʁa/}} → {{IPA|[ʁa]}} ('rat'), vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|ras}} {{IPA|/ʁɑ/}} → {{IPA|[ʁɑ]}} ('short')

There are certain environments that prefer one open vowel over the other. For example, {{IPA|/ɑ/}} is preferred after {{IPA|/ʁw/}} and before {{IPA|/z/}}:
: {{wikt-lang|fr|trois}} {{IPA|[tʁwɑ]}} ('three'),
: {{wikt-lang|fr|gaz}} {{IPA|[ɡɑz]}} ('gas').{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|p=64}}

The difference in quality is often reinforced by a difference in length (but the difference is contrastive in final closed syllables). The exact distribution of the two vowels varies greatly from speaker to speaker.<ref>"For example, some have the front {{IPA|[a]}} in {{wikt-lang|fr|casse}} 'breaks', and the back {{IPA|[ɑ]}} in {{wikt-lang|fr|tasse}} 'cup', but for others the reverse is true. There are also, of course, those who use the same vowel, either {{IPA|[a]}} or {{IPA|[ɑ]}}, in both words".{{Harvcoltxt|Tranel|1987|p=48}}</ref>

Back {{IPA|/ɑ/}} is much rarer in unstressed syllables, but it can be encountered in some common words:
: {{wikt-lang|fr|château}} {{IPA|[ʃɑ.to]}} ('castle'),
: {{wikt-lang|fr|passé}} {{IPA|[pɑ.se]}} ('past').

Morphologically complex words derived from words containing stressed {{IPA|/ɑ/}} do not retain it:
: {{wikt-lang|fr|âgé}} {{IPA|/ɑʒe/}} → {{IPA|[aː.ʒe]}} ('aged', from {{wikt-lang|fr|âge}} {{IPA|/ɑʒ/}} → {{IPA|[ɑʒ]}})
: ''rarissime'' {{IPA|/ʁaʁisim/}} → {{IPA|[ʁaʁisim]}} ('very rare', from {{wikt-lang|fr|rare}} {{IPA|/ʁɑʁ/}} → {{IPA|[ʁɑʁ]}}).

Even in the final syllable of a word, back {{IPA|/ɑ/}} may become {{IPA|[a]}} if the word in question loses its stress within the extended phonological context:{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|p=64}}
: ''J'ai été au '''bois''''' {{IPA|/ʒe ete o bwɑ/}} → {{IPA|[ʒe.e.te.o.bwɑ]}} ('I was in the woods'),
: ''J'ai été au '''bois''' de Vincennes'' {{IPA|/ʒe ete o bwɑ dəvɛ̃sɛn/}} → {{IPA|[ʒe.e.te.o.bwad.vɛ̃.sɛn]}} ('I was in the Vincennes woods').

===Nasal vowels===
The phonetic qualities of the back nasal vowels are not very similar to those of the corresponding oral vowels, and the contrasting factor that distinguishes {{IPA|/ɑ̃/}} and {{IPA|/ɔ̃/}} is the extra lip rounding of the latter according to some linguists,{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=74}} but other linguists have come to the conclusion that the main difference is in tongue height.{{sfnp|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=33-34}} Speakers who produce both {{IPA|/œ̃/}} and {{IPA|/ɛ̃/}} distinguish them mainly through increased lip rounding of the former, but many speakers use only the latter phoneme, especially most speakers in northern France such as Paris (but not farther north, in [[Belgium]]).{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=74}}{{sfnp|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=33-34}}

In some dialects, particularly that of Europe, there is an attested tendency for nasal vowels to shift in a counterclockwise direction: {{IPA|/ɛ̃/}} tends to be more open and shifts toward the vowel space of {{IPA|/ɑ̃/}} (realised also as {{IPA|[æ̃]}}), {{IPA|/ɑ̃/}} rises and rounds to {{IPA|[ɔ̃]}} (realised also as {{IPA|[ɒ̃]}}) and {{IPA|/ɔ̃/}} shifts to {{IPA|[õ]}} or {{IPA|[ũ]}}. Also, there also is an opposite movement for {{IPA|/ɔ̃/}} for which it becomes more open and unrounds to {{IPA|[ɑ̃]}}, resulting in a merger of Standard French {{IPA|/ɔ̃/}} and {{IPA|/ɛ̃/}} in this case.{{sfnp|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=33-34}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Hansen|first=Anita Berit|title=Les voyelles nasales du français parisien moderne. Aspects linguistiques, sociolinguistiques et perceptuels des changements en cours|year=1998|publisher=Museum Tusculanum Press|isbn=87-7289-495-4|language=French}}</ref> In Quebec French, two of the vowels shift in a different direction: {{IPA|/ɔ̃/}} → {{IPA|[õ]}}, more or less as in Europe, but {{IPA|/ɛ̃/}} → {{IPA|[ẽ]}} and {{IPA|/ɑ̃/}} → {{IPA|[ã]}}.<ref>[https://www.internationalphoneticassociation.org/icphs-proceedings/ICPhS2011/OnlineProceedings/RegularSession/Carignan/Carignan.pdf Oral articulation of nasal vowel in French]</ref>

===Schwa===
When phonetically realised, [[schwa]] ({{IPAslink|ə}}), also called ''e {{wikt-lang|fr|caduc}}'' ('dropped e') and ''e {{wikt-lang|fr|muet}}'' ('mute e'), is a mid-central vowel with some rounding.{{sfnp|Fougeron|Smith|1993|p=73}} Many authors consider it to be phonetically identical to {{IPAslink|œ}}.{{sfnp|Anderson|1982|p=537}}{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|p=88}} Geoff Lindsey suggests the symbol {{IPAslink|ɵ}}.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lindsey|first1=Geoff|title=Le FOOT vowel|url=http://englishspeechservices.com/blog/le-foot-vowel/|website=English Speech Services|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lindsey|first1=Geoff|title=Rebooting Buttocks|url=http://englishspeechservices.com/blog/rebooting-buttocks/|website=English Speech Services|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref> {{Harvcoltxt|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006}} state, more specifically, that it merges with {{IPAslink|ø}} before high vowels and glides:
: {{wikt-lang|fr|netteté}} {{IPA|/nɛtəte/}} → {{IPA|[nɛ.tø.te]}} ('clarity'),
: {{wikt-lang|fr|atelier}} {{IPA|/atəlje/}} → {{IPA|[a.tø.lje]}} ('workshop'),
in phrase-final stressed position:
: ''dis-le !'' {{IPA|/di lə/}} → {{IPA|[di.lø]}} ('say it'),
and that it merges with {{IPAslink|œ}} elsewhere.{{sfnp|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=59}} However, some speakers make a clear distinction, and it exhibits special phonological behavior that warrants considering it a distinct phoneme. Furthermore, the merger occurs mainly in the French of France; in Quebec, {{IPAslink|ø}} and {{IPAslink|ə}} are still distinguished.<ref>[http://www.afcp-parole.org/doc/Archives_JEP/2008_XXVIIe_JEP_Avignon/PDF/avignon2008_pdf/JEP/072_jep_1653.pdf Timbre du schwa en français et variation régionale : un étude comparative] retrieved 14 July 2013</ref>

The main characteristic of French schwa is its "instability": the fact that under certain conditions it has no phonetic realisation.
* That is usually the case when it follows a single consonant in a medial syllable:
*: {{wikt-lang|fr|rappeler}} {{IPA|/ʁapəle/}} → {{IPA|[ʁap.le]}} ('to recall'),
* It is most frequently mute in word-final position:
*: {{wikt-lang|fr|table}} {{IPA|/tabl(ə)/}} → {{IPA|[tabl]}} ('table').
* Word-final schwas are optionally pronounced if preceded by two or more consonants and followed by a consonant-initial word:
*: ''une porte fermée'' {{IPA|/yn(ə) pɔʁt(ə) fɛʁme/}} → {{IPA|[yn.pɔʁ.t(ə).fɛʁ.me]}} ('a closed door').
* In the future and conditional forms of ''-er'' verbs, however, the schwa is sometimes deleted even after two consonants:
*: ''tu garderais'' {{IPA|/ty ɡaʁdəʁɛ/}} → {{IPA|[ty.ɡaʁ.d(ə.)ʁɛ]}} ('you would guard'),
*: ''nous brusquerons [les choses]'' {{IPA|/nu bʁyskəʁɔ̃/}} → {{IPA|[nu.bʁys.k(ə.)ʁɔ̃]}} ('we will precipitate [things]').
* On the other hand, it is pronounced word-internally when it follows more pronounced consonants that cannot be combined into a complex onset with the initial consonants of the next syllable:
*: {{wikt-lang|fr|gredin}} {{IPA|/ɡʁədɛ̃/}} → {{IPA|[ɡʁə.dɛ̃]}} ('scoundrel'),
*: ''sept petits'' {{IPA|/sɛt pəti/}} → {{IPA|[sɛt.pə.ti]}} ('seven little ones').{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|pp=88–105}}

Pronouncing {{IPA|[ə]}} as {{IPA|[œ]}} is a way to emphasise the syllable.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} For instance, pronouncing {{wikt-lang|fr|biberon}} ('baby bottle') {{IPA|[bi.bœ.ʁɔ̃]}} instead of {{IPA|[bib.ʁɔ̃]}} is a way to draw attention to the {{angbr|e}} (to clarify the spelling, for example).

In French versification, word-final schwa is always elided before another vowel and at the ends of verses. It is pronounced before a following consonant-initial word.{{sfnp|Casagrande|1984|pp=228–29}} For example, ''une grande femme fut ici ''{{IPA|[yn ɡʁɑ̃d fam fy.t‿i.si]}}, would be pronounced {{IPA|[y.nə ɡʁɑ̃.də fa.mə fy.t‿i.si]}}, with the {{IPA|/ə/}} at the end of each word being pronounced.

Schwa cannot normally be realised as a front vowel ({{IPAblink|œ}}) in closed syllables. In such contexts in inflectional and derivational morphology, schwa usually alternates with the front vowel {{IPAslink|ɛ}}:
: {{wikt-lang|fr|harceler}} {{IPA|/aʁsəle/}} → {{IPA|[aʁ.sœ.le]}} ('to harass'), with
: ''il harcèle'' {{IPA|/il aʁsɛl/}} → {{IPA|[i.laʁ.sɛl]}} ('[he] harasses').{{sfnp|Anderson|1982|pp=544–46}}

A three-way alternation can be observed, in a few cases, for a number of speakers:
: {{wikt-lang|fr|appeler}} {{IPA|/apəle/}} → {{IPA|[ap.le]}} ('to call'),
: ''j'appelle'' {{IPA|/ʒ‿apɛl/}} → {{IPA|[ʒa.pɛl]}} ('I call'),
: {{wikt-lang|fr|appellation}} {{IPA|/apelasjɔ̃/}} → {{IPA|[a.pe.la.sjɔ̃]}} ('brand'), which can also be pronounced {{IPA|[a.pɛ.la.sjɔ̃]}}.<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=63}} for {{IPAblink|e}}, TLFi, s.v. ''[http://www.cnrtl.fr/definition/appellation appellation]'' for {{IPA|[ɛ]}}.</ref>

Instances of orthographic {{angbr|e}} that do not exhibit the behaviour described above may be better analysed as corresponding to the stable, full vowel {{IPA|/œ/}}. The [[enclitic]] pronoun {{wikt-lang|fr|le}}, for example, always keeps its vowel in contexts like ''donnez-le-moi'' {{IPA|/dɔne lə mwa/}} → {{IPA|[dɔ.ne.lœ.mwa]}} ('give it to me') for which schwa deletion would normally apply (giving *{{IPA|[dɔ.nɛl.mwa]}}), and it counts as a full syllable for the determination of stress.

Cases of word-internal stable {{angbr|e}} are more subject to variation among speakers, but, for example, ''un rebelle'' {{IPA|/ɛ̃ ʁəbɛl/}} → {{IPA|[ɛ̃.ʁœ.bɛl]}} ('a rebel') must be pronounced with a full vowel in contrast to ''un rebond'' {{IPA|/ɛ̃ ʁəbɔ̃/}} → {{IPA|[ɛ̃.ʁœ.bɔ̃]}} or {{IPA|[ɛ̃ʁ.bɔ̃]}} ('a bounce').{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|pp=98–99}}

===Length===
Except for the distinction still made by some speakers between {{IPA|/ɛ/}} and {{IPA|/ɛː/}} in rare minimal pairs like  {{wikt-lang|fr|mettre}} {{IPA|[mɛtʁ]}} ('to put') vs. {{wikt-lang|fr|maître}} {{IPA|[mɛːtʁ]}} ('teacher'), variation in vowel length is entirely allophonic. Vowels can be lengthened in closed, stressed syllables, under the following two conditions:

*{{IPA|/o/}}, {{IPA|/ø/}}, {{IPA|/ɑ/}}, and the nasal vowels are lengthened before any consonant: {{wikt-lang|fr|pâte}} {{IPA|[pɑːt]}} ('dough'), {{wikt-lang|fr|chante}} {{IPA|[ʃɑ̃ːt]}} ('sings').
*All vowels are lengthened if followed by one of the voiced fricatives—{{IPA|/v/}}, {{IPA|/z/}}, {{IPA|/ʒ/}}, {{IPA|/ʁ/}} (not in combination)—or by the cluster {{IPA|/vʁ/}}: {{wikt-lang|fr|mer}}/{{wikt-lang|fr|mère}} {{IPA|[mɛːʁ]}} ('sea/mother'), {{wikt-lang|fr|crise}} {{IPA|[kʁiːz]}} ('crisis'), {{wikt-lang|fr|livre}} {{IPA|[liːvʁ]}} ('book').{{sfnp|Walker|1984|pp=25–27}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Tranel|1987|pp=49–51}} However, words such as ''(ils) servent'' {{IPA|[sɛʁv]}} ('(they) serve') or {{wikt-lang|fr|tarte}} {{IPA|[taʁt]}} ('pie') are pronounced with short vowels since the {{IPA|/ʁ/}} appears in clusters other than {{IPA|/vʁ/}}.

When such syllables lose their stress, the lengthening effect may be absent. The vowel {{IPA|[o]}} of {{wikt-lang|fr|saute}} is long in ''Regarde comme elle saute !'', in which the word is phrase-final and therefore stressed, but not in ''Qu'est-ce qu'elle saute bien !''{{sfnp|Walker|2001|p=46}} In accents wherein {{IPA|/ɛː/}} is distinguished from {{IPA|/ɛ/}}, however, it is still pronounced with a long vowel even in an unstressed position, as in ''fête'' in ''C'est une fête importante.''{{sfnp|Walker|2001|p=46}}

