===Devoicing===
In Parisian French, the close vowels {{IPA|/i, y, u/}} and the mid front {{IPA|/e, ɛ/}} at the end of utterances can be [[devoiced]]. A devoiced vowel may be followed by a sound similar to the [[voiceless palatal fricative]] {{IPA|[ç]}}:
: ''Merci.'' {{IPA|/mɛʁsi/}} → {{IPA|[mɛʁ.si̥ç]}} ('Thank you.'),
: ''Allez !'' {{IPA|/ale/}} → {{IPA|[a.le̥ç]}} ('Go!').{{sfnp|Fagyal|Moisset|1999}}

In Quebec French, close vowels are often devoiced when unstressed and surrounded by voiceless consonants:
: ''université'' {{IPA|/ynivɛʁsite/}} → {{IPA|[y.ni.vɛʁ.si̥.te]}} ('university').{{sfnp|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=27}}
Though a more prominent feature of Quebec French, phrase-medial devoicing is also found in European French.{{sfnp|Torreira|Ernestus|2010}}

===Elision===
{{Main|Elision (French)}}

The final vowel (usually {{IPA|/ə/}}) of a number of monosyllabic [[function word]]s is [[elision|elided]] in syntactic combinations with a following word that begins with a vowel. For example, compare the pronunciation of the unstressed subject pronoun, in ''je dors'' {{IPA|/ʒə dɔʁ/}} {{IPA|[ʒə.dɔʁ]}} ('I am sleeping'), and in ''j'arrive'' {{IPA|/ʒ‿aʁiv/}} {{IPA|[ʒa.ʁiv]}} ('I am arriving').

===Glides and diphthongs===
The glides {{IPA|[j]}}, {{IPA|[w]}}, and {{IPA|[ɥ]}} appear in syllable onsets immediately followed by a full vowel. In many cases, they alternate systematically with their vowel counterparts {{IPA|[i]}}, {{IPA|[u]}}, and {{IPA|[y]}} such as in the following pairs of verb forms:
:''nie'' {{IPA|[ni]}}; {{wikt-lang|fr|nier}} {{IPA|[nje]}} ('deny')
:''loue'' {{IPA|[lu]}}; {{wikt-lang|fr|louer}} {{IPA|[lwe]}} ('rent')
:''tue'' {{IPA|[ty]}}; {{wikt-lang|fr|tuer}} {{IPA|[tɥe]}} ('kill')
The glides in the examples can be analysed as the result of a glide formation process that turns an underlying high vowel into a glide when followed by another vowel: {{IPA|/nie/}} → {{IPA|[nje]}}.

This process is usually blocked after a complex onset of the form obstruent + liquid (a stop or a fricative followed by {{IPA|/l/}} or {{IPA|/ʁ/}}). For example, while the pair ''loue''/''louer'' shows an alternation between {{IPA|[u]}} and {{IPA|[w]}}, the same suffix added to ''cloue'' {{IPA|[klu]}}, a word with a complex onset, does not trigger the glide formation: ''clouer'' {{IPA|[klue]}} ('to nail'). Some sequences of glide + vowel can be found after obstruent-liquid onsets, however. The main examples are {{IPA|[ɥi]}}, as in ''pluie'' {{IPA|[plɥi]}} ('rain'), {{IPA|[wa]}}, and {{IPA|[wɛ̃]}}.<ref>The latter two correspond to orthographic {{angbr|oi}}, as in ''trois'' {{IPA|[tʁwa]}} ('three'), which contrasts with disyllabic ''troua'' {{IPA|[tʁu.a]}} ('[he] punctured').</ref> They can be dealt with in different ways, as by adding appropriate contextual conditions to the glide formation rule or by assuming that the phonemic inventory of French includes underlying glides or rising [[diphthong]]s like {{IPA|/ɥi/}} and {{IPA|/wa/}}.{{sfnp|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|pp=37–39}}{{sfnp|Chitoran|2002|p=206}}

Glide formation normally does not occur across morpheme boundaries in compounds like ''semi-aride'' ('semi-arid').{{sfnp|Chitoran|Hualde|2007|p=45}} However, in colloquial registers, ''si elle'' {{IPA|[si.ɛl]}} ('if she') can be pronounced just like {{wikt-lang|fr|ciel}} {{IPA|[sjɛl]}} ('sky'), or ''tu as'' {{IPA|[ty.ɑ]}} ('you have') like ''tua'' {{IPA|[tɥa]}} ('[he] killed').{{sfnp|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=39}}

The glide {{IPA|[j]}} can also occur in syllable coda position, after a vowel, as in {{wikt-lang|fr|soleil}} {{IPA|[sɔlɛj]}} ('sun'). There again, one can formulate a derivation from an underlying full vowel {{IPA|/i/}}, but the analysis is not always adequate because of the existence of possible minimal pairs like {{wikt-lang|fr|pays}} {{IPA|[pɛ.i]}} ('country') / {{wikt-lang|fr|paye}} {{IPA|[pɛj]}} ('paycheck') and {{wikt-lang|fr|abbaye}} {{IPA|[a.bɛ.i]}} ('abbey') / {{wikt-lang|fr|abeille}} {{IPA|[a.bɛj]}} ('bee').<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fagyal|Kibbee|Jenkins|2006|p=39}}. The words ''pays'' and ''abbaye'' are more frequently pronounced {{IPA|[pe.i]}} and {{IPA|[abe.i]}}.</ref> Schane (1968) proposes an abstract analysis deriving postvocalic {{IPA|[j]}} from an underlying lateral by palatalization and glide conversion ({{IPA|/lj/}} → {{IPA|/ʎ/}} → {{IPA|/j/}}).{{sfnp|Schane|1968|pp=57–60}}

==Stress==
Word stress is not distinctive in French, so two words cannot be distinguished on the basis of stress placement alone. In fact, grammatical stress is always on the final full syllable (syllable with a vowel other than schwa) of a word. Monosyllables with schwa as their only vowel ({{wikt-lang|fr|ce}}, {{wikt-lang|fr|de}}, {{wikt-lang|fr|que}}, etc.) are generally [[clitic]]s but otherwise may receive stress.{{sfnp|Anderson|1982|p=537}}

The difference between stressed and unstressed syllables in French is less marked than in English. Vowels in unstressed syllables keep their full quality, regardless of whether the rhythm of the speaker is syllable-timed or mora-timed (see [[isochrony]]).<ref>Mora-timed speech is frequent in French, especially in Canada, where it is very much the norm.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}</ref> Moreover, words lose their stress to varying degrees when pronounced in phrases and sentences. In general, only the last word in a phonological phrase retains its full grammatical stress (on its last full syllable).{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|pp=194–200}}

===Emphatic stress===
Emphatic stress is used to call attention to a specific element in a given context such as to express a contrast or to reinforce the emotive content of a word. In French, this stress falls on the first consonant-initial syllable of the word in question. The characteristics associated with emphatic stress include increased amplitude and pitch of the vowel and gemination of the onset consonant, as mentioned [[#Geminates|above]].{{sfnp|Tranel|1987|pp=200–201}} Emphatic stress does not replace, but occurs in tandem with, grammatical stress.{{sfnp|Walker|2001|pp=181—2}}
*''C'est parfaitement vrai''. {{IPA|[sɛ.paʁ.fɛt.mɑ̃.ˈvʁɛ]}} ('It's perfectly true.'; no emphatic stress)
*''C'est '''par'''faitement vrai.'' {{IPA|[sɛ.ˈp(ː)aʁ.fɛt.mɑ̃.ˈvʁɛ]}} (emphatic stress on ''parfaitement'')

For words that begin with a vowel, emphatic stress falls on the first syllable that begins with a consonant or on the initial syllable with the insertion of a glottal stop or a [[liaison (French)|liaison]] consonant.
*''C'est é'''pouv'''antable.'' {{IPA|[sɛ.te.ˈp(ː)u.vɑ̃ˈ.tabl]}} ('It's terrible.'; emphatic stress on second syllable of ''épouvantable'')
*''C'est '''é'''pouvantable !'' {{IPA|[sɛ.ˈt(ː)e.pu.vɑ̃.ˈtabl]}} (initial syllable with liaison consonant {{IPA|[t]}})
*''C'est '''é'''pouvantable !'' {{IPA|[sɛ.ˈʔe.pu.vɑ̃.ˈtabl]}} (initial syllable with glottal stop insertion)

==Intonation==

{{Main|Intonation (linguistics)#French}}

French intonation differs substantially from that of English.{{sfnp|Lian|1980}} There are four primary patterns:

*The continuation pattern is a rise in pitch occurring in the last syllable of a rhythm group (typically a phrase).
*The finality pattern is a sharp fall in pitch occurring in the last syllable of a declarative statement.
*The yes/no intonation is a sharp rise in pitch occurring in the last syllable of a yes/no question.
*The information question intonation is a rapid fall-off from high pitch on the first word of a non-yes/no question, often followed by a small rise in pitch on the last syllable of the question.

