"'''Pornoviolence'''" is an essay by American author [[Tom Wolfe]]. It first appeared under a longer title in the July 1967 issue of ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' magazine,<ref name=esquire>{{cite journal|last=Wolfe|first=Tom|title=Pause, Now, and Consider Some Tentative Conclusions About the Meaning of This Mass Perversion Called Porno-Violence: What It Is and Where It Came from and Who Put the Hair on the Walls|journal=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|date=July 1967|page=54}}</ref> and was later published in the collection ''[[Mauve Gloves & Madmen, Clutter & Vine]]''.<ref name=mauve>{{cite book|last=Wolfe|first=Tom|author-link=Tom Wolfe|title=[[Mauve Gloves & Madmen, Clutter & Vine]]|publisher=[[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]]|location=New York|isbn=0374204241|pages=178–187|chapter=Pornoviolence|year=1976|lccn=76043968}}</ref> The essay introduced the term "pornoviolence" in reference to graphic written or audiovisual depictions of violence, which Wolfe argued were used in newspapers, magazines, and film to stimulate prurient audience interest.
The essay was intended to decry the media's habit of glorifying violence as a way of gratifying their audience, in the same way a [[pornographic film]] does using sex. Aside from attacking [[popular culture]], such as the articles of ''[[The National Enquirer]]'' and its imitators, Wolfe also levels his criticism at more mainstream art, including [[Truman Capote]]'s controversial [[non-fiction novel]] ''[[In Cold Blood]]''. He argues that, in the absence of mystery and the unpredictable, Capote's book retains the audience's attention with the promise of disclosing gruesome details about the [[true crime]] it discusses, thus degenerating the work to the level of sadistic sensationalism, or, indeed, pornoviolence.
"Pornoviolence" as a term has subsequently been used to disparage excessively violent content in books, horror films, and video games.<ref name=kingdanse>{{cite book|last=King|first=Stephen|title=[[Danse Macabre (book)|Danse Macabre]]|publisher=Everest House|location=New York|isbn=9780896960763|page=132|year=1981}}</ref><ref name=hoberman>{{cite encyclopedia | last = Hoberman | first = J. | authorlink = | editor-first = Jeffrey H. | editor-last = Goldstein | editor-link = Jeffrey H. Goldstein | encyclopedia = Why We Watch: The Attractions of Violent Entertainment | title = "A test for the individual viewer": Bonnie and Clyde's violent reception | url = http://is.muni.cz/el/1421/jaro2010/FAVz020/hoberman_1998.pdf | accessdate = 2 February 2014 | year = 1998 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = New York | isbn = 9780195353440 | pages = 116–143 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140202050451/http://is.muni.cz/el/1421/jaro2010/FAVz020/hoberman_1998.pdf | archivedate = 2 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=boldt>{{cite news|last=Boldt|first=David R.|title='Bonnie and Clyde' was the start of all the 'pornoviolence' on film|url=http://articles.philly.com/1993-08-01/news/25967115_1_bonnie-and-clyde-clyde-barrow-depression-era-bank-robbers|accessdate=2 February 2014|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=1 August 1993|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202051242/http://articles.philly.com/1993-08-01/news/25967115_1_bonnie-and-clyde-clyde-barrow-depression-era-bank-robbers|archivedate=2 February 2014|deadurl=no|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|page=E5}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Graphic violence]] * [[Aestheticization of violence]] * [[Media violence research]] * "[[Torture porn]]", a term coined by critic [[David Edelstein]] in 2005 for pornoviolence-saturated horror films
