* /w/ is the only initial consonant permitted to form [[consonant cluster]]s with other consonants.
* {{IPA|/p/}} occurs syllable-initially only in [[loan word]]s, and is mostly converted into {{IPA|/ɓ/}} (as in ''sâm banh'', derived from French ''champagne'').
* The glottalized stops are preglottalized and voiced:  {{IPA|[ʔɓ, ʔɗ]}} (the [[glottis]] is always closed before the oral closure). This glottal closure is often not released before the release of the oral closure, resulting in the characteristic [[implosive]] pronunciation. However, sometimes the glottal closure is released prior to the oral release in which case the stops are pronounced {{IPA|[ʔb, ʔd]}}. Therefore, the primary characteristic is preglottalization with implosion being secondary.
* {{IPA|/ɓ, m/}} are [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]], while {{IPA|/f, v/}} are [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]].
* {{IPA|/t, tʰ/}} are [[Denti-alveolar consonant|denti-alveolar]] ({{IPA|[t̪, t̪ʰ]}}), while {{IPA|/ɗ, n, l/}} are [[Apical consonant|apico]]-[[alveolar consonant|alveolar]].<ref name="Kirby 382">{{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=382}}</ref>
* {{IPA|/c, ɲ/}} are phonetically [[Laminal consonant|lamino]]-[[palatoalveolar]]  (the blade of the tongue makes contact behind the [[alveolar ridge]]).
* {{IPA|/ʈ, c/}} are often slightly [[affricate]]d {{IPA|[ʈ͡ʂ, t͡ɕ]}}, but they are [[Aspiration (phonetics)|unaspirated]].
* A [[glottal stop]] {{IPA|[ʔ]}} is inserted before words that begin with a vowel or {{IPA|/w/}}:

:{| cellpadding="5" style="line-height: 1.0em;"
| ''ăn''
| 'to eat'
| {{IPA|/ăn/}}
| →
| {{IPA|[ʔăn]}}
|-
| ''uỷ''
| 'to delegate'
| {{IPA|/wi/}}
| →
| {{IPA|[ʔwi]}}
|}

===Hanoi initials===
* {{IPA|/s, z/}} are [[Laminal consonant|laminal]].<ref name="Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965"/>
* ''d'', ''gi'' and ''r'' are all pronounced {{IPA|/z/}}.
* ''ch'' and ''tr'' are both pronounced {{IPA|/c/}}, while ''x'' and ''s'' are both pronounced {{IPA|/s/}}.

===Saigon initials===
* {{IPA|/s/}} is [[Apical consonant|apical]].<ref name="Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965"/>
* ''d'' and ''gi'' are both pronounced {{IPA|/j/}}.
* Historically, {{IPA|/v/}} is pronounced {{IPA|[j]}}, merging with ''d'' and ''gi''. However, it is becoming distinct and pronounced as {{IPA|[v]}}.
* Historically, a distinction is made between ''ch'' {{IPA|/c/}} and ''tr'' {{IPA|/ʈ/}}, as well as between ''x'' {{IPA|/s/}} and ''s'' {{IPA|/ʂ/}}. However, these two pairs are becoming merged as {{IPA|/c/}} and {{IPA|/s/}} respectively.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Phạm|2008|p=35}}</ref>
* In southern speech, the phoneme {{IPA|/r/}}, generally represented in Vietnamese linguistics by the letter {{angbr|r}}, has a number of variant pronunciations that depend on the speaker. More than one pronunciation may even be found within a single speaker. It may occur as a [[Voiced retroflex fricative|retroflex fricative]] {{IPA|[ʐ]}}, an [[alveolar approximant]] {{IPA|[ɹ]}}, a [[Alveolar tap|flap]] {{IPA|[ɾ]}} or a [[Alveolar trill|trill]] {{IPA|[r]}}.

