===Hanoi finals===
====Analysis of final ''ch'', ''nh''====

The pronunciation of syllable-final ''ch'' and ''nh'' in Hanoi Vietnamese has had different analyses. One analysis, that of {{Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965}} has them as being phonemes {{IPA|/c, ɲ/}}, where {{IPA|/c/}} contrasts with both syllable-final ''t'' {{IPA|/t/}} and ''c'' {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/ɲ/}} contrasts with syllable-final ''n'' {{IPA|/n/}} and ''ng'' {{IPA|/ŋ/}}. Final {{IPA|/c, ɲ/}} is, then, identified with syllable-initial {{IPA|/c, ɲ/}}.

Another analysis has final {{angbr|ch}} and {{angbr|nh}} as representing predictable [[allophonic]] variants of the velar phonemes {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/ŋ/}} that occur after upper front vowels {{IPA|/i/}} (orthographic {{angbr|i}}) and {{IPA|/e/}} (orthographic {{angbr|ê}}). This analysis interprets orthographic ⟨ach⟩ and ⟨anh⟩ as an underlying {{IPA|/ɛ/}}, which becomes phonetically open and diphthongized: {{IPA|/ɛk/}} → {{IPA|[ăjk̟̚]}}, {{IPA|/ɛŋ/}} → {{IPA|[ăjŋ̟]}}.<ref>Although there are some words where orthographic {{angbr|c}} and {{angbr|ng}} occur after {{IPA|/ɛ/}}, these words are few and are mostly loanwords or [[onomatopoeia]]</ref> This diphthongization also affects ⟨êch⟩ and ⟨ênh⟩: {{IPA|/ek/}} → {{IPA|[ə̆jk̟̚]}}, {{IPA|/eŋ/}} → {{IPA|[ə̆jŋ̟]}}.

Arguments for the second analysis include the limited distribution of final {{IPA|[c]}} and {{IPA|[ɲ]}}, the gap in the distribution of {{IPA|[k]}} and {{IPA|[ŋ]}} which do not occur after {{IPA|[i]}} and {{IPA|[e]}}, the pronunciation of ⟨ach⟩ and ⟨anh⟩ as {{IPA|[ɛc]}} and {{IPA|[ɛɲ]}} in certain conservative central dialects,<ref name="rhyme"/> and the patterning of {{IPA|[k]}}~{{IPA|[c]}} and {{IPA|[ŋ]}}~{{IPA|[ɲ]}} in certain reduplicated words. Additionally, final {{IPA|[c]}} is not articulated as far forward as the initial {{IPA|[c]}}: {{IPA|[c]}} and {{IPA|[ɲ]}} are pre-velar {{IPA|[k̟, ŋ̟]}} with no alveolar contact.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=383}}</ref>

The first analysis closely follows the surface pronunciation of a slightly different Hanoi dialect than the second. In this dialect, the {{IPA|/a/}} in {{IPA|/ac/}} and {{IPA|/aɲ/}} is not diphthongized but is actually articulated more forward, approaching a front vowel {{IPA|[æ]}}. This results in a three-way contrast between the rimes ''ăn'' {{IPA|[æ̈n]}} vs. ''anh'' {{IPA|[æ̈ɲ]}} vs. ''ăng'' {{IPA|[æ̈ŋ]}}. For this reason, a separate phonemic {{IPA|/ɲ/}} is posited.

